<title type="html"><![CDATA[Why is Brazil &quot;PAL&quot;?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=3511&amp;p=26097#p26097"><![CDATA[
Yeah, something like Fx3 said. I understand that, by definition, PAL-M is a type of PAL but... still... If you read that Brazil uses PAL, you'll assume that PAL games are playable here, PAL movies are watchable here... which almost never is the case.<br /><br />Of course, it would be wrong to list Brazil as an "NTSC country", because that's also not true. But in practice, if you send an NTSC signal to an old PAL-M TV, you'll get the picture just fine, but without color. But if you try a PAL signal, you'll get an unwatchable rolling image. Based on that I'd say PAL-M is much closer to NTSC than to PAL.<br /><br />I don't know much about video signals, I admit! =)<br /><br />I wonder if this kind of thing happens to other countries, which are not PAL, SECAM or NTSC, and just have one of those 3 (incorrectly) assigned to them in that picture.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=95">tokumaru</a> — Wed Aug 01, 2007 9:38 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
